GSEM factor analysis - datadriven

AA & JP

12 July, 2024

Standard factor models

Here, I test standard latent factor models that are suggested by exploratory factor analysis (data-driven). Instead of using half the chromosomes for EFA and the other half for CFA, I just used the full genome for both. For some of the traits the signal is quite localized, so that even and odd chromosomes are unlikely to share signal. Instead of focusing on absolute fit, we will compare models and focus on relative fit.

We use promax rotation everywhere, free all first indicator loadings, and restrain all factor variance to 1. I allow for cross loadings. The minimum factor loading is set to 0.3 throughout. Where necessary, variance is forced to be >0.

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.14.TOT.RData')

CFA <- '
F1 =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + ALCFRQ + COCDEP + CANEV + SMKINI + SMKAGE
F2 =~ NA*CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + SMKAGE
F3 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP 
F4 =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI

F1~~1*F1

semPlotModel_GSEM=function(gsem.object=GWISoutput , est.label="STD_All"){ 
      
       object=gsem.object$results
       object$free=0
       numb=1:length(which(object$op!="~~"))
       object$free[which(object$op!="~~")]=numb
       varNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "ov")
       factNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "lv")
       factNames <- factNames[!factNames %in% varNames]
       n <- length(varNames)
       k <- length(factNames)
       if (is.null(object$label)) 
         object$label <- rep("", nrow(object))
       semModel <- new("semPlotModel")
       object$est <- object[,est.label]
       object$se <- object[,"STD_Genotype_SE"]
       
       if (is.null(object$group)) 
         object$group <- ""
       semModel@Pars <- data.frame(label = object$label, lhs = ifelse(object$op == 
                                                                        "~" | object$op == "~1", object$rhs, object$lhs), edge = "--", 
                                   rhs = ifelse(object$op == "~" | object$op == "~1", object$lhs, 
                                                object$rhs), est = object$est, std = NA, group = object$group, 
                                   fixed = object$free==0, par = object$free, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~*~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~"] <- "~>"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "=~"] <- "->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~1"] <- "int"
       semModel@Pars$edge[grepl("\\|", object$op)] <- "|"
       semModel@Thresholds <- semModel@Pars[grepl("\\|", semModel@Pars$edge), 
                                            -(3:4)]
       semModel@Pars <- semModel@Pars[!object$op %in% c(":=", "<", 
                                                        ">", "==", "|", "<", ">"), ]
       semModel@Vars <- data.frame(name = c(varNames, factNames), 
                                   manifest = c(varNames, factNames) %in% varNames, exogenous = NA, 
                                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@ObsCovs <- list()
       semModel@ImpCovs <- list()
       semModel@Computed <- FALSE
       semModel@Original <- list(object)
       return(semModel)
       
}

CFA:

I had to fix the loading of cocaine dependence on factor 2 to 1 in order to get the model to converge (unfixed the loading was >100). Even under that restriction I had to fix the variance of F2 to 1 to estimate the model. The fit is not great and the loading from cocaine dependence on F3 is negative, while the other indicators have a risk-increasing direction. F3 is a messy factor.

Conclusion

The EFA-suggested models are not very clean, though a 4-factor solution does show excellent fit statistics. The first factor in all models has a lot of indicators with cross loadings. It seems that the first factor captures a general latent liability, justifying the testing of bifactor models.
